caption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig08b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.303095156/asset/images/095156fig08b.jpeg" height="1581" width="1655" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.303095156&amp;id=fig08b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig09a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.303095156/asset/images/095156fig09a.jpeg" height="1601" width="1692" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.303095156&amp;id=fig09a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig09b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.303095156/asset/images/095156fig09b.jpeg" height="1500" width="1602" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.303095156&amp;id=fig09b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.303095156/asset/images/095156fig10a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1777" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.303095156&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.303095156/asset/images/095156fig10b.jpeg" height="1190" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.303095156&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.303095156/asset/images/095156fig11.jpeg" height="1800" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span> Epiglottitis in an 18-year-old woman with dyspnea. Lateral neck radiograph demonstrates marked bulbous thickening of the epiglottis, a finding known as the thumb sign.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.303095156&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.303095156/asset/images/095156fig12.jpeg" height="1800" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span> Neck radiograph obtained in a pediatric patient shows a normal subglottic airway with a normal convex shape of the shoulders.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.303095156&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.303095156/asset/images/095156fig13a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1364" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.303095156&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.303095156/asset/images/095156fig13b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1408" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.303095156&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.303095156/asset/images/095156fig14.jpeg" height="1800" width="1392" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span> Pharyngeal foreign body in a 3-year-old girl with dysphagia. Lateral neck radiograph shows a curvilinear radiopaque foreign body lodged within the oropharynx and hypopharynx (arrows). A fishbone was extracted.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.303095156&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.303095156/asset/images/095156fig15a.jpeg" height="1476" width="1408" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.303095156&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.303095156/asset/images/095156fig15b.jpeg" height="1224" width="1141" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.303095156&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.303095156/asset/images/095156fig16.jpeg" height="1800" width="1763" aria-labelledby="fig16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16</span> Peritonsillar abscess in a 17-year-old boy with fever, sore throat, and trismus. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image demonstrates a peripherally enhancing fluid collection in the left peritonsillar region (arrow). Note the mass effect on the oropharynx.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.303095156&amp;id=fig16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.303095156/asset/images/095156fig17.jpeg" height="882" width="1280" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span> Infected thyroglossal duct cyst in an 8-year-old boy with a midline neck mass. Color Doppler US image obtained in the anterior part of the neck shows an anechoic cystic structure with a thickened irregular wall and hyperemia, findings suggestive of superinfection of a thyroglossal duct cyst.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.303095156&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.303095156/asset/images/095156fig18.jpeg" height="1797" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18</span> Thyroglossal duct cyst in a 14-year-old boy with neck swelling. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image depicts a rounded region of hypoattenuation within the left strap muscles at the level of the thyroid cartilage.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.303095156&amp;id=fig18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.303095156/asset/images/095156fig19.jpeg" height="1743" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig19" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19</span> Second branchial cleft cyst in a 6-year-old boy with a neck mass. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image demonstrates a rounded region of hypoattenuation (arrow) with a location anteromedial to the sternocleidomastoid muscle (arrowhead), findings characteristic of a second branchial cleft cyst.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.303095156&amp;id=fig19">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.303095156/asset/images/095156fig20a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1738" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.303095156&amp;id=fig20a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.303095156/asset/images/095156fig20b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1468" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.303095156&amp;id=fig20b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.303095156/asset/images/095156fig20c.jpeg" height="1800" width="1585" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20c</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.303095156&amp;id=fig20c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.303095156/asset/images/095156fig21a.jpeg" height="1069" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.303095156&amp;id=fig21a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.303095156/asset/images/095156fig21b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1520" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.303095156&amp;id=fig21b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.303095156/asset/images/095156fig22.jpeg" height="1602" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig22" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22</span> Tuberculous adenitis in a 12-year-old boy with a palpable neck mass. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT image demonstrates suppurative adenopathy involving multiple level V lymph nodes in the right side of the neck. Aspirate obtained with a fine-needle biopsy contained acid-fast bacilli.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.303095156&amp;id=fig22">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.303095156/asset/images/095156fig23.jpeg" height="1589" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig23" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23</span> Nodal metastasis in a 20-year-old man with a left-sided neck mass. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image depicts a large left jugulodigastric lymph node with internal necrosis and irregular peripheral enhancement. Squamous cell carcinoma was found at nodal biopsy, and a primary tongue neoplasm was subsequently identified.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.303095156&amp;id=fig23">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.303095156/asset/images/095156fig24a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1499" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.303095156&amp;id=fig24a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.303095156/asset/images/095156fig24b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1567" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.303095156&amp;id=fig24b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.303095156/asset/images/095156fig25.jpeg" height="1800" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig25" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25</span> Suppurative lateral retropharyngeal node in an 11-month-old girl with left-sided neck swelling. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image depicts a peripherally enhancing fluid collection (arrow) in a location medial to the left internal carotid artery, a finding suggestive of an abscess within the lateral retropharyngeal node.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.303095156&amp;id=fig25">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.303095156/asset/images/095156fig26.jpeg" height="1274" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig26" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26</span> Fibromatosis colli. Gray-scale US image obtained in a 1-month-old girl with a right-sided neck mass demonstrates a focal, fusiform area of thickening in the sternocleidomastoid muscle (arrowheads).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.303095156&amp;id=fig26">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.303095156/asset/images/095156fig27a.jpeg" height="1144" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.303095156&amp;id=fig27a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f